</code></pre>
Excerpt From: Apple Inc. “The Swift Programming Language.”

You can add your own operator overloading of different number types to mitigate the casting required see:
<a href="https://github.com/jquave/EasyCast" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/jquave/EasyCast</a><p>You can also add your own String extension for length and index character at in a String with:<p><pre><code>    extension String {
        var length: Int { return countElements(self) }

        subscript (i: Int) -> String {
            return String(Array(self)[i])
        }
    }
</code></pre>
Which will now let you use `.length` on strings, e.g:<p><pre><code>    &quot;Cat&quot;.length; //3
</code></pre>
And get the character at index with:<p><pre><code>    &quot;Cat&quot;[1]; //a
</code></pre>
I&#x27;ve more useful extensions at: <a href="https://github.com/mythz/swift-linq-examples/blob/master/src/LinqExamples/extensions.swift" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/mythz/swift-linq-examples/blob/master/src...</a><p>Which enables LINQ-like querying in Swift: <a href="https://github.com/mythz/swift-linq-examples" rel="nofollow">https://github.com/mythz/swift-linq-examples</a>
